To us you're a "Very Important Passenger"
-a V. I. P. You are flying in a shining new
Constellation,
fastest carrier of the Air
Transport Command.
Today it is an airline transport-swift, pow-
erful, superbly dependable. You are one of
the first commercial travelers to actually en-
joy its pleasures. We want you to know the
airplane-its contribution to modern air
travel - what makes it great! This booklet
will make you a well-informed V.I.P.

properties.sfomuseum:description: Flight information packet issued by TWA (Trans World Airlines), comprising:a. folder with illustrated cover; bi-fold format with two pockets;b, c. luggage label; oval-shaped label with airline wordmark and illustration of aircraft in flight;d. passenger record / flight log, titled “Flight facts from your Captain”; bi-fold format;e. customer comment form, titled “If you please”; self-folding envelope;f. postcard with full color photographic image of Lockheed Constellation in flight;g, h. postcard with full color photographic image of Boeing 306 “Stratoliner” in flight;i. ticket booklet and receipt, dated March 8, 1946, for flight from Shannon to New York, passenger R. Gerson;j. ticket booklet and receipt, dated March 8, 1946, for flight from Shannon to New York, passenger H. Gerson;k. ticket booklet and receipt, dated March 8, 1946, for flight from Shannon to New York, passenger N. Gerson;l. brochure promoting Lockheed Constellation service; fold-out format;m. brochure with TWA facts and history; fold-out format;n. timetable effective March 1946; folded multipage booklet.
